1. Add the following packages to the pom.xml :




    <dependency>  
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>  
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-redis</artifactId>  
    </dependency>

This will ensure all the necessary packages are added for you to connect to
Redis.

2\. Create an application.properties file in the /resources directory :



    # Redis Configuration  
    spring.redis.host=localhost  
    spring.redis.port=6379

3\. Create a @Configuration class for setting up Redis as below :



    package com.joel.myspring.shared.config;  

    import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Qualifier;  
    import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;  
    import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;  
    import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;  
    import org.springframework.data.redis.connection.RedisConnectionFactory;  
    import org.springframework.data.redis.connection.lettuce.LettuceConnectionFactory;  
    import org.springframework.data.redis.core.RedisTemplate;

**

Till this point, pretty much straightforward, as we just need to Auto-wire the
RedisTemplate bean to get started on using the Redis connection we have
established.

But now , to establish a second connection, we will make use of Named Beans
and Qualifiers. Also, we will need to disable a few default auto-configuration
flags set by Spring Boot.

  1. Start by making these changes to the RedisConfig class :



